comments.body:
@dkg  Speaking in my personal capacity.

I think this issue is important, especially for use cases that are derived from existing legal or protective frameworks such as IHL.

From that perspective, it may be useful for each use case to identify the relevant roles without turning those roles into separate legal conclusions or protocol obligations. For example, an IHL-related use case may need to distinguish between:

- the protected asset or bearer;
- the entity operating or controlling the asset;
- the competent authorizing entity, where authorization is required;
- the emblem issuer or entity publishing the digital marking;
- the validator or party checking whether DIEM-interpretable data exists and can be validated;
- and possible misuse or adverse actors, such as parties falsely claiming a protected status.

I would be careful with trying to model the “attacker” perspective too fully. In contemporary armed conflicts, the range of possible actors, motivations, operational settings, and legal contexts can be very broad, so any such model would likely need to remain high-level and non-exhaustive.

For that reason, I think it may be more useful to capture only a minimal and non-canonical adverse-actor perspective, just enough to help derive technical requirements. For IHL-related use cases, that could include questions such as whether a party may try to ignore, misuse, falsify, or probe a digital emblem, and whether the design should account for false claims, revocation, authorization, or undetectable validation.

So perhaps the use cases could include a lightweight role model, while leaving legal, operational, and accountability conclusions outside the DIEM requirements document.

@rahelFain Speaking in my personal capacity.

I think this issue is delicate because forensic tracing may be important for some use cases, but it may also be outside the core scope of DIEM.

From an IHL-related use case perspective, there may be situations where, after a cyber operation or other incident, different parties may want to reconstruct what information was available, discoverable, or technically verifiable at a relevant point in time. For example, the relevant question may not only be whether an emblem was valid, but whether DIEM-related data existed, was discoverable, could be validated, or was associated with an applicable authorization model.

At the same time, I do not want to suggest that the core DIEM mechanism should become a forensic, audit, or accountability system. That may belong to a later implementation stage, a profile-specific extension, an external registry/logging mechanism, or another system entirely.

Making forensic tracing a mandatory core property could create tension with:

- undetectable validation;
- minimization of sensitive information;
- protection of staff, facilities, infrastructure, or affected populations;
- and avoiding exposure of who queried or validated a protected asset.

For that reason, I would lean toward treating forensic tracing as outside the core DIEM mechanism, or at most as a profile-specific or extension-specific capability.

However, I think the requirements document could still acknowledge the question at a high level, so implementers do not assume that DIEM itself provides forensic or evidentiary guarantees.

Could the chairs/editors provide guidance on where this belongs?

Should the requirements document:

- merely acknowledge forensic/audit support as a possible use-case-specific need;
- define an extension point for future profiles;
- mention it only in Security Considerations;
- or leave it entirely to external systems and later implementation work?

@rohanmahy Speaking in my personal capacity.

I think this issue is useful, but I would be careful about treating all listed examples as automatically within the same scope or as the same kind of “emblem” use case.

Some examples may be connected to existing legal frameworks, treaties, conventions, regulatory regimes, or technical certification systems. Others may involve critical infrastructure or protected-status signaling in a broader sense. However, that does not necessarily mean that each example should be treated as a digital emblem use case in the same way, or that it should be included in this requirements draft.

From an IHL-related perspective, I think this distinction matters because not every protected, regulated, critical, or sensitive asset has the same legal basis, protective meaning, authorization model, or expected validator behavior.

For that reason, could the chairs/editors provide guidance on the threshold for including additional potential emblem types in this draft?

For example, should a candidate use case identify at least:

- the legal, treaty, regulatory, policy, or technical-standard source of the claimed status;
- whether the mark is an existing emblem/sign, a regulated label, a certification signal, or a future protected-status marking;
- who is competent to authorize, issue, or validate the marking;
- what technical information the validator is expected to learn;
- whether the use case requires public discoverability, selective disclosure, confidentiality, or undetectable validation;
- and which legal, operational, or accountability conclusions remain outside DIEM.

This may help avoid merging very different categories into one broad “emblem” concept.

I am not suggesting that the listed examples are invalid. I am only suggesting that additional use cases may need a scope filter before being added to the draft, so the architecture remains extensible without implying that all protected, regulated, or critical assets have the same legal meaning or should be handled under the same profile.

@rohanmahy Speaking in my personal capacity.

I think this issue is useful because it may help separate different discovery questions without requiring the draft to prescribe a specific post-DNS mechanism at this stage.

For IHL-related or other legally-derived use cases, I would distinguish at least three conceptual layers:

- discovering or identifying the relevant asset name or asset identifier;
- determining whether the returned data, bundle, or associated material is interpretable as DIEM-related data;
- validating that the DIEM-related data is properly bound to the relevant asset and issued or authorized under the applicable trust model.

I am not proposing a new DNS label, a new RRtype, or any particular post-DNS discovery syntax. My point is only that future discovery mechanisms may need to preserve the same functional separation: asset identification, DIEM-data discovery, and technical validation.

This may be especially relevant for protected assets that do not map cleanly to a single FQDN, or where the physical-world protected object, the digital service, and the validating party do not all share the same operational view of the asset.

So perhaps the requirements could remain mechanism-neutral, while noting that any future post-DNS discovery mechanism should make clear:

- what asset or identifier is being queried;
- what makes the returned material interpretable as DIEM-related;
- how the validator checks binding, authorization, and validity;
- and which legal, operational, or policy interpretation remains outside the discovery mechanism itself.

I agree with the concern that DIEM itself should not become a forensic, audit, or governance system.

At the same time, I think it may still be useful for the use cases and requirements document to identify when a use case has evidentiary expectations, so that future profile or implementation work does not accidentally assume that DIEM solved those questions.

In my view, “proof of presence” may be clearer if it is treated as a set of use-case-specific evidentiary questions, rather than as one mandatory protocol feature. For example, a use case may need to say whether it cares about:

- existence of DIEM-interpretable data;
- discoverability of that data;
- access to the data;
- validation of signatures or bindings;
- response content at a relevant time;
- or later conduct by a party.

These are different questions, and not all of them are compatible with undetectable validation.

I would also avoid framing audit evidence as a mechanism to identify every visitor or validator. For IHL-related use cases, undetectable validation may be important precisely because a validator should be able to check an emblem or protected-status marking without alerting the asset.

So perhaps the core document only needs to say that proof/audit mechanisms, where required, are use-case-specific and may be external to the core DIEM mechanism. The core DIEM work can remain focused on discovery and technical validation, while the use case text makes clear that forensic or audit expectations are not automatically solved by the protocol.

I think this PR raises an important terminology issue.

From an IHL perspective, it may be useful to make clear that DIEM is not creating a new legal category of emblems. Rather, for IHL-related use cases, DIEM appears to be exploring how existing protective emblems, distinctive signs, or protected-status markings may be represented, discovered, and validated in the digital environment.

In that sense, I would be careful with any new umbrella term that could be understood as defining a new legal category. Names used in the draft for use cases could be descriptive and provisional, not normative.

For example, the draft could distinguish between use case labels such as:

- digital representation of medical/humanitarian protective emblems;
- digital representation of the civil defence distinctive sign;
- digital representation of the cultural property emblem;
- digital representation of the dangerous-forces special sign;
- future protected-status markings for other IHL-related use cases, where legally and operationally justified.

These labels would only help describe use cases for technical analysis. They should not imply that the WG is creating new emblems or deciding final legal terminology.

Any formal naming, recognition, or legal categorization of new protective emblems or signs should remain a matter for the relevant legal and diplomatic processes, including the competent authorities and, where applicable, the High Contracting Parties, not the technical contributors defining use cases.

This may help preserve the distinction between:

- the legal status or protective meaning of an existing emblem/sign;
- the technical mechanism for representing or validating it digitally;
- and the descriptive label used in the draft for a use case.

```suggestion
- The emblems of the Red Cross, Red Crescent, and Red Crystal, defined in the Geneva Conventions and Additional Protocol III of the Geneva Conventions {{GCI1949}} {{APIII2005}}
- The Blue Shield emblem, defined in the 1954 Hague Convention {{HAGUE1954}}
- The international distinctive sign of civil defence, defined in Additional Protocol I of the Geneva Conventions {{API1977}}
- The dangerous forces special sign, defined in Additional Protocol I of the Geneva Conventions {{API1977}}
```

Thank you for this PR. I think the response-requirements discussion is important, especially for use cases where visibility is part of the protective function of the emblem or protected-status marking.

One possible way to clarify the issue may be to distinguish response layers:

1. discovery/existence of DIEM data for an asset;
2. a minimal profile or category hint;
3. a reference, digest, or locator for the full DIEM object;
4. the full signed emblem or protected-status object;
5. proof-of-presence or audit evidence, if required by the specific use case.

Under this model, a profile could require consistent discovery of the existence of DIEM data for asset X, while still allowing selective or variable full content depending on requester attributes, geography, authorization, access policy, or operational context.

For example, a minimal DNS/DIEM response could indicate only that DIEM data exists and that validation should be triggered:

```dns
_diem.hospital.example. IN DIEM "v=1; presence=1; profile=ihl-medical-humanitarian; digest=sha256-abc123; ref=https://diem-authority.example/records/abc123"
```

This would not be the full emblem object. It would only tell a DIEM-aware client:

```text
DIEM data exists for this asset.
The profile is medical/humanitarian.
Validation should be triggered.
The full signed object can be located or verified using the reference/digest.
```

A different IHL-related profile could use the same discovery pattern without reusing humanitarian or medical emblem semantics. For example, cultural property:

```dns
_diem.museum.example. IN DIEM "v=1; presence=1; profile=ihl-cultural-property; digest=sha256-def456; ref=https://diem-authority.example/records/def456"
```

In that case, the full signed object could provide the profile-specific semantics:

```json
{
  "version": "DIEM1",
  "asset": {
    "id": "museum.example",
    "type": "fqdn"
  },
  "profile": {
    "id": "ihl-cultural-property",
    "family": "ihl"
  },
  "marking": {
    "kind": "protected-status",
    "physical_equivalent": "blue-shield"
  },
  "issuer": {
    "id": "cultural-authority.example"
  },
  "validity": {
    "not_before": "2026-01-01T00:00:00Z",
    "not_after": "2027-01-01T00:00:00Z"
  },
  "revocation": {
    "status": "valid",
    "uri": "https://diem-authority.example/status/def456"
  },
  "signature": "base64url-signature"
}
```

For an installation containing dangerous forces, the discovery response could remain minimal, while the full content may need to be selective or minimized:

```dns
_diem.dam.example. IN DIEM "v=1; presence=1; profile=ihl-dangerous-forces-installation; digest=sha256-ghi789; ref=https://diem-authority.example/records/ghi789"
```

The full object might identify the protected-status profile without exposing unnecessary technical details:

```json
{
  "version": "DIEM1",
  "asset": {
    "id": "dam.example",
    "type": "fqdn"
  },
  "profile": {
    "id": "ihl-dangerous-forces-installation",
    "family": "ihl"
  },
  "marking": {
    "kind": "protected-status",
    "physical_equivalent": "three-bright-orange-circles",
    "asset_category": "dam"
  },
  "issuer": {
    "id": "authorized-infrastructure-authority.example"
  },
  "validation": {
    "digest": "sha256-ghi789",
    "revocation_uri": "https://diem-authority.example/status/ghi789"
  },
  "signature": "base64url-signature"
}
```

For a civilian essential service that may not correspond to an existing physical emblem, the profile could avoid claiming humanitarian or medical emblem semantics:

```dns
_diem.water.example. IN DIEM "v=1; presence=1; profile=ihl-civilian-essential-service; sector=water; digest=sha256-jkl012; ref=https://diem-authority.example/records/jkl012"
```

The full object could make the distinction explicit:

```json
{
  "version": "DIEM1",
  "asset": {
    "id": "water.example",
    "type": "fqdn"
  },
  "profile": {
    "id": "ihl-civilian-essential-service",
    "family": "ihl",
    "sector": "water"
  },
  "marking": {
    "kind": "protected-status",
    "physical_equivalent": null,
    "not_humanitarian_emblem": true
  },
  "issuer": {
    "id": "civilian-infrastructure-authority.example"
  },
  "validation": {
    "digest": "sha256-jkl012",
    "revocation_uri": "https://diem-authority.example/status/jkl012"
  },
  "signature": "base64url-signature"
}
```

These examples are not proposed syntax. They are only intended to illustrate the distinction between:

- a minimal discovery/existence response;
- a profile/category hint;
- a reference or digest for validation;
- and the full signed object with profile-specific semantics.

This distinction may help separate two different questions:

- “Can a DIEM-aware client discover that DIEM data exists for this asset?”
- “Does every requester receive the same full emblem or protected-status object?”

For some profiles, consistent discoverability of DIEM data for asset X may be important because visibility is part of the protective function. However, the full content may still be selective, minimized, or profile-dependent.

In short, perhaps the draft could distinguish between:

- consistent discoverability of DIEM data for an asset;
- consistency or selectivity of the full emblem/protected-status content;
- and proof-of-presence or audit evidence, where required by the use case.

This might preserve the visibility function of certain emblems or protected-status markings while still allowing DNS-based deployments to support selective responses or selective content where a use case requires it.

@rahelFain  @felixlinker 

Small clarification based on the mailing-list discussion:

The DNS snippets in my earlier comment were only illustrative. I am not proposing a `_diem` label, a `DIEM` RRtype, or a separate discovery mechanism.

I would restate my point more narrowly:

A DIEM-aware validator queries the relevant asset name, inspects the returned RRsets or bundle, determines whether the returned data is interpretable as DIEM, validates the relevant signatures or bindings, and then presents a limited technical result.

The distinction I was trying to make is between:

- discovery that DIEM-interpretable data exists for an asset;
- validation of the relevant signatures or bindings;
- whether the full content is consistent or selective;
- and proof or audit evidence, if required by a specific use case, which may belong outside the core DIEM mechanism.

So the point is not to prescribe DNS syntax. The point is to separate discovery, validation, response consistency, selective content, and downstream proof/audit concerns.

@felixlinker 

A shorter way to frame “applying an emblem” in this context may be:

Applying a digital emblem means binding an emblem or protected-status marking to a specific asset through the mechanisms defined by the relevant DIEM profile, so that a DIEM-aware validator can discover and validate the associated data.

That technical binding should not be understood as creating the legal protection by itself. The underlying status comes from the applicable legal framework and authorization model. The digital emblem makes the claimed status discoverable and technically verifiable.

This may help keep the distinction between:

- the digital marker or representation;
- the underlying protected status;
- the authorization model;
- and the validation process.

The new draft can be found at
[https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-diem-requirements/](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-diem-requirements/ 
)
